FRA Inspector Harrington found tank car NPLX 208359, load of alcohols, n.o.s. with an audible vapor leak coming from the manway area.  leak was reported to Norfolk Southern Haz Mat Team.  Haz Mat Team requested a approved ER contractor respond.  Contractor fond all manway bolts tight and were unable to stop the leak by tightening.  The bolts were loosened and the manway opened.  Flat gasket in manway cover was split, allowing vapors to escape.  Contractor replaced with new gasket and re-secured the manway bolts on the car.  No detect on meter after securement.  Car released back in to transportation.

column43: sodium hydroxide solution and saw dust
column168: While attempting to weigh 55 gallon open head poly drum of corrosive liquid (sodium hydroxide solution containing sawdust) at Veolia's 10-DAY transportation warehouse storage area in Port Allen, LA, the drum slipped out of the drum grabber attachment that was being used in conjunction with our forklift. The drum fell ~6-8 inches to the floor causing the lid to pop off of the drum. As a result, approximately 250 ml of the sludge material within the container splashed on to the floor of the warehouse.  The Veolia employee immediately applied absorbent material on top of the spilled material and reclosed the drum. While closing drum it was noticed the closure ring on top of the drum had a little bit of paint chipped off and was slightly bent.  The Veolia employee immediately informed the supervisor who then reported the incident to appropriate personnel and determined how to proceed in regards to this event.  The drum was overpacked into a salvage drum to continue transportation.
column169: The shipment was a brokered load that was shipped to Veolia.  Veolia will follow up with the customer to remind them of proper container selection when loading hazardous materal/waste.  Veolia will also recommend to not package material similar to this to such a high capacity within poly open head drums, since poly drums are less rigid than metal drums, thus allowing container to shift and deform when heavy materials apply force to them. This shift/deformation makes the container more likely to fail in ways similar to what happened in this incident.

On 04/13/2021 at 0927 hours EST CSXT personnel in the Southover Yard ( Savannah, GA) discovered TAMX1030, a loaded tank car of Dimethylaminoethanol leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Eastman Chemical / Taminco US LLC was notified. HEPACO, a CSXT  response contractor, responded along with Hazmat Manager James and found the product leaking  from under the flange of the liquid line where it meets the pressure plate. The issue was identified  and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Eastman (Lisa Feathers 423-229-3398).  HEPACO transferred the product from TAMX1030 to tank car TAMX1010. TAMX1030 has been cleaned and purged and is awaiting an OTMA-3 to move to home shop for repairs. The car is on hold pending repairs coordinated by the shipper. While attempting to add the listed product name Dimethylaminoethanol as the proper name it was not listed, I used Ethanolamine as the material name.

column43: Waste Flammable Liquids, Petroleum Distallate, Xylene
column168: On 04/06/2021, at 1205, personnel in the CSXT Defiance Yard discovered SRIX 80415, a loaded tank car of Waste Flammable Liquids, N.O.S., leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, Ohio EPA, the local LEPC and Local Fired Department were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2021-0406-000190). Enviroserve, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found multiple leak points from the bottom of the car, emanating from beyond the tank jacket interface, suggesting a tank shell failure. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative Mr. Joseph Eskra of the Lubrizol Corporation, phone 440-364-9372. Contractor personnel secured a secondary containment system, and then performed an emergency transfer of the car's content's into tank trucks, and finally cleaned and purged the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.   Cause Code: 652 NARRI: 36

column168: On 4/06/2021 a Veolia employee noticed there was a small drip from a intermediate bulk container on a Veolia vehicle at ESI in South Windsor, CT. The leak occurred on a box truck in the ESI 10 day transfer area prior to Veolia employees transferring the container to a tractor trailer. Employees saw the leak when they started to transfer the waste with a pallet jack to move the IBC into a trailer.  Employees opened the container and noticed a very sludge-like material that had free liquid in it. Additionally some large debris items were placed in the container for disposal by the shipper. Additional speedi-dri was added to the container to absorb free liquid in the container.    The container was observed for a day to ensure it stopped leaking prior to reoffering it for continued transportation to the ultimate disposal facility. The total amount of material that leaked from the container was estimated to be about 1 pint of class 9 hazardous waste. It is opined that the large objects that were placed in the container caused a tear in the liner of the IBC. The liquid was cleaned up with spill pads and speedi-dri was added to the IBC to stop the leaking  The duration of release is anticipated to be a small drip from the drum for about 12 hours with no more than a pint leaking. The leak was contained to the truck and did not reach outside the vehicle. The Veolia safety manager of Marlborough, MA was notified and the Connecticut DEEP was also notified. The shipper was notified of the leak and will use drums in the future to avoid leaks with the material.
column169: The shipper will load the material into drums in the future to avoid leaks.

column168: On 4/16/2021 at 2000 personnel in the CSXT Moncrief Yard discovered GATX 60885, a loaded  tank car of Crude Sulfate Turpentine leaking vapor from top of the tank car. Hulls Environmental,  a CSXT response contractor and Josh Dearing Manager of Hazardous Material for CSX, was  dispatched to the scene and found 3 of 6 manway safety bolts less than tool tight.  Upon  inspection the manway was opened and found that the manway gasket was not properly in  place and damaged. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper  Julie Baty, 804-317-0434. Contractor personnel replaced the manway gasket with a new gasket  and tool tightened the manway safety bolts and no decontamination of the tank car was needed.   The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special  switching  move.

Contractor personnel inspected the manway cover gasket to ensure it was free of damage, properly secured all manway cover bolts, and the car was released for transportation.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper via CHEMTREC (Report 2021-0419-00293)

TRAILER WITH HAZMAT ARRIVED ON DOOR 05 AT 6:45AM. HAZMAT WAS UNLOADED AND PALLED AT 6:50AM. IT TRAVELLED DOWN THE UNLOAD BELT ONTO A SLIDE LEADING TO THE 100/200 (NORTH SIDE) BELT WHERE IT WAS IMMDIATELY NOTICED BY THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER. HAZMAT WAS NOT ACTIVELY LEAKING BUT APPEARED WET. D.R. STOPPED PROGRESSION OF HAZMAT, DONNED PPE, FOLLOWED THE DECICION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET. D.R. FOLLOWED THE HAZMATS PROGRESS THROUGH THE BUILDING TO FIND WHERE IT HAD COME FROM AND FOUND A MINOR SPILL IN TRAILER #382344 FROM OAKLAND. D.R. CLEANED UP AND REMOVED SPILL SAFETLY. THE SMALL SPILL IN THE TRAILER IN ADDITION TO THE PATTERN OF WETNESS INSIDE OF THE OUTER CARTON OF THE HAZMAT LEADS TO THE ASSUMPTION THAT THE HAZMAT WAS IMPROPERLY BRACED ON ALL FOUR SIDES AND TIPPED OVER ON ITS SIDE MINUTES BEFORE BEING UNLOADED, MOST LIKELY WHILE THE TRAILER WAS BEING PUT ON THE DOOR. THIS PLUS A LOOSE LID CAUSED THE SPILL.

I RESPONDED TO PD-10 FOR A SPILL. I USED THE DECISION TREE AND FLAMMABLE RESPONSE SHEET TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND COLLECTED MATERIAL. THEN TAKEN TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. UPON THE RESPONSE, I NOTICED THAT THE PACKAGE WAS DROPPED AND THAT'S WHAT CAUSED THE SPILL.

column168: Driver had previously completed a load securement check approximately 1 hour before the leak was discovered and had specifically looked at the bottom  discharge of the tanker trailer. There was no evidence of a leak at the time. The driver had exhausted his HOS for the shift and had stopped at a hotel for the night. When he was conducting his post trip inspection, he noticed a few drips of liquid on the ground and identified the source as a failed welded seam on a stainless steel reinforcement plate where the bottom discharge elbow attached to the trailer body. He immediately placed a containment under the drip and pulled a slight vacuum on the trailer. This stopped the drip and prevented any more material from being released.
column169: Inspection and maintenance records were reviewed for this trailer to ensure that all were current. The VIK and all maintenance was within the acceptable time frames and nothing was delinquent. The Branch was instructed to inspect all other DOT 407 trailers to check for visible defects in the welded seams in the area where the leak originated from. No other trailers had visible defects. The trailer that leaked was taken to a truck wash and put in the shop for diagnostics and repairs immediately. The driver maintained periodic load securement checks and was able to observe and mitigate the leak soon after it began.

column168: I ARRIVED AT THE SPILL WITH ALL MY PPE FULLY EQUIPPED AND ARRIVED TO UNLOAD WEST DOOR 10. I NOTICED THE LEAKING HAZMAT ON THE GROUND AND EXAMINED THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX AND NOTICED THAT IT HAD TWO DIAMOND HAZARD LABELS ON IT, WHICH WERE OXIDIZER   CORROSIVE.  USING PH TAPE I DETERMINED WHAT LIQUID IT WAS ON THE GROUND AND USED SODIUM BICARBONATE AND ZEP ZORBENT TO SOLIDFY THE LIQUID. I GRABBED A WOONDEN STICK FROM MY SPILL CART TO MIX EVERYTHING UP IN ORDER TO PUT IT IN MY SPILL TRAY. I PLACED THE HAZMAT PACKAGE ON MY SPILL CART TO TAKE IT BACK TO DMP FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

On April 16, 2021 AT 1130 et, Landstar truck #570523 and trailer #668530 were involved in a single - vehicle, rollover accident. As a result, all cargo, (18) 1,000 KG bulk bags of UN3077, Environmentally hazardous substance, solid, nos (4,4'-Dichlorodiphenyl sulfone),9, PGIII, MARINE POLLUTANT were damaged and released all contents, roughly 39,683 pounds impacting the soil alongside the roadway. Hepaco was dispatched out of Ashland, KY to perform emergency response and cleanup activities. The contractor excavated the impacted area of soil after removing the debris. Impacted soil was placed into three (3) roll off boxes. Final site restoration is still pending.

column168: After picking up UPS Whites Creek, two Veolia employees proceeded to their next stop at Tesla. When the employees got into the back of the truck they noticed a drum was starting to bulge. The employees noticed it was the drum of Peracetic acid that was repacked into a poly drum while onsite at UPS. As the drum continued to bulge Veolia employees cleared the back of the truck and made sure to warn the customer that they were going to hear a "pop". After a minute or two the drum popped the top off and the Veolia employees could see the fumes from the reaction coming from the drum. After checking that it was safe, the truck was pulled into a vacant parking lot away from the building. Veolia employees donned APR respirators and Tyvek suits to enter the back and remediate the drum. The drum contained two green bags each containing 3 or 4 containers of product. 3 bottles from one bag were completely empty and 4 from the other were completely intact. Veolia believes the reaction was from the three bottles contents leaking onto the absorbent used by UPS (possibly cat litter or oil dry. the absorbent was very fine.) The product was separated from the absorbent but still had some reaction in the vermiculite. The material was then soaked with ~15 gallons of cold water and the reaction stopped soon after.  Veolia has not had any further issues with the two containers of separated material.
column169: Moving forward Veolia will be rejecting any bags that contain damaged or leaking peroxyacetic or peroxyacetic spill clean up. (i.e. If Veolia arrives on site and we notice the bag has vermiculite or spill dry inside or the bottle is leaking we would reject the drum until UPS soaks the contents of the bag with water.) Veolia will only package any bottles that are not damaged or leaking.

On 04/15/2021, at 0747 hours, personnel in the CSXT Brooklyn Junction Yard discovered MTZX 330092, a residue tank car of Propane, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, West Virginia DEP, and FRA were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report 2021-0415-00126). Specialized Professional Services, Inc, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapor valve one quarter turn in the open position and the secondary closure plug not tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Mr. Mark Holloway of Amerigas, phone 832-577-8841. Contractor personnel closed the valve, properly installed the secondary closure plug. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.  Cause Code: 136 NARRI: 90

column168: On 4/27/21, ODOT inspector C. Kuenzi identified the CTCX 300880 as possibly venting vapor through the Vaccum Relief Valve (VRV). Estimated volumes released are the best estimate given information provided by responders.

The delivery hose the driver was using has camlock ends that lock the hoses on to the customer fittings.  While unloading the camlocks popped open and the hose came off.  Because the customer fill line is a vertical fill line when it came off under pressure it sprayed up under his face shield and impacted his lower face and lips.  It also forced his goggles up with the force of impact and got the corner of his eye.  He grabbed a water hose next to the unloading area  used to flush delivery hoses out with (grabbed it out of instinct he said) vs going around the corner to the safety shower and started rinsing down.  An employee spotted him and brought him over to the shower.  After showing for 20 minutes he was taken to the hospital and treated and released.
column169: Thankfully the driver had on all the correct PPE.  However, he stated he forgot to wrap the camlock connections down with tape as per our training and processes.  There is also an element to this where a properly fitted hose should not allow for any movement of the camlocks when properly hooked up.  The tape is just an extra security measure.  We brought him back in for training on both of these pieces.  In follow up with him several weeks later he is feeling normal / good.

column168: On 04/25/2021, at 1308 hours, personnel in the CSXT Willard Yard discovered SHPX 211040, a loaded tank car of Combustible Liquid, N.O.S., leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, Ohio EPA, and local Fire Department were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report 2021-0425-00024). Specialized Professional Services, Inc., a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found 6 of 6 manway cover bolts not applied or secured. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Mr. Art Board of LyondellBasel, phone 713-857-0471. Contractor personnel secured all manway cover bolts and cleaned all spilled material from the exterior of the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.  Cause Code: 200 NARRI: 60

column168: On April 18, 2021 at 0940 ET, one (1) 330 - gallon tote containing UN2810, Toxic liquid, organic, nos (hexahydro 1,3,5-TRIS(2-HYDROXYETHLY)-S-TRIAZINE, METHANOL), 6.1, PGII "RSI-13W" was discovered to be leaking from a crack. Haz-Mat Response was dispatched to the site to perform cleanup activities. Upon the contractor's arrival, personnel confirmed an 8' by 3' area of the trailer floor and two areas of the asphalt parking lot measuring 8' by 4" were all impacted by a total of approximately 15 gallons of RSI-13W. The applied granular absorbents to the impacted mediums. The spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55 - gallon poly drum. Haz-Mat Response personnel then transferred the product remaining in the compromised tote into a new tote. The tote was loaded into the trailer and the contractor departed the site with the drum of waste generated and the damaged tote.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: On April 23, 2021, personnel at the R+L Carriers (RLC) terminal located at the above-referenced address observed a cargo leak at dock doors 27 and 28. One (1) 330-gallon tote of UN1830 sulfuric acid split open when placed on the dock floor and released 330 gallons of product to the dock and pavement. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES), who dispatched a crew from Environmental Restoration, LLC (ER) to perform the necessary corrective action. ER personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted concrete floor and impacted pavement surfaces outside the dock. ER utilized a vacuum unit and hand tools recover the product and impacted absorbents into poly drums. Impacted pallets and debris were collected in drums for disposal as well. All waste was collected and containerized into eighteen (18) 55-gallon poly drums for disposal. The three (3) undamaged product totes were transferred into new 330-gallon poly totes as a precaution. Once the cleanup was complete and approved by the terminal staff, ER staged the waste drums onsite and demobilized.

On April 20, 2021 at 1218 ET, a load shift occurred on Landstar trailer #668457. As a result, one (1) 55 - gallon poly drum containing UN1760, Corrosive liquid, nos (Potassium Hydroxide), 8, PGII "Bulk Kleen 842HP" was compromised. As a result, approximately 15 gallons of Bulk Kleen 842HP released impacting the trailer floor and asphalt below the trailer. Patriot Environmental Services was dispatched to the site. The contractor applied granular absorbents to the impacted area of asphalt and the impacted trailer floor. The spent absorbents were collected and containerized into two (2) 55 - gallon poly drums. The damaged drum was overpacked into one (1) 95 - gallon overpack drum. Patriot Environmental Services personnel then departed the site with the waste generated.

column42: HYDROGEN, PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 40 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: On 4/23/21 at 0900 ET, the cap of one (1) 275 - gallon poly tote was noticed to be loose when unloading. As a result, approximately 2 gallons of Sunlite released impacting the trailer floor and asphalt below. ERS of OK was dispatched to the site to perform cleanup activities. The contractor was able to re-secure the cap. The impacted trailer and asphalt were decontaminated with sodium bicarbonate to neutralize and solidify the released product. The spent absorbents and utilized PPE were placed into one (1) 55 - gallon drum. The area was then rinsed and the rinse water was captured with a drum vacuum. The contractor then departed the site with the waste generated.

column168: On April 29, 2021, at approximately 12:30 a.m. CST, a tractor-trailer operated by R+L Carriers (RLC) caught fire and burned at the above-referenced location. The tractor and forward trailer of the tandem trailer unit (OA4519) were severely damaged by the fire. As a result, the tractor released approximately (50) gallons of diesel fuel to the roadway and adjacent soil drainage ditch. The cargo in the trailer included 55-gallon metal drums of UN1866 resin solution which were damaged in the fire and released resin solution to the soil ditch and surface water. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES), who dispatched a crew from Enviroserve, Inc. (ESI) to perform the necessary corrective action. ES deployed absorbent boom and dams to contain the release in the ditch line. Crews recovered the remaining resin drums and loaded into a lined roll-off box for disposal. The roll-off box was transported to the RLC terminal in Columbiana to be staged for profiling. ES utilized a vacuum truck to recover impacted surface water from the ditch. ES mobilized a mini excavator and skid steer to perform a surface scrape of the impacted soils. The impacted soils were loaded into one (1) roll-off box for transport and disposal. The excavation was then seeded and strawed. Absorbent boom was left in the ditch to capture any residual.

column168: A Veolia trailer arrived at the facility gate to deliver at the Veolia, Azusa facility. After exiting the Vehicle, the driver noticed a drop of liquid on the asphalt. He looked down and noticed wet spot around the center of the trailer bed and immediately notified the receiving department. The facility accepted the trailer at the offloading dock with containment already prepared for hazardous waste, offloaded the drums from and trailer and located a leaky drum. It appeared that there was a small dent at the bottom of the drum that may have created pinhole from vibration during transportation. The leaking drum was overpacked.
column169: Veolia informed the shipper of this incident.  The Veolia field personnel have been reminded to thoroughly check all containers for good integrity prior to transportation.

column168: Univar Solutions driver was making a minibulk delivery to customer Chemart.  We fill a smaller 250 gallon tank and a customer’s employee transfers the acid at the same time to a larger tank.   Once driver started offload, Chemart EE 1 began to transfer into their larger tank.  During this transfer, the customer’s EE 1 asked driver to watch the tank for him so he could take care of something.  Driver watched tank with no issues then shortly after the customer’s EE 1 came back and said he was taken over and Driver returned to his trailer.   5 minutes later customer EE 2 ran out of the building and said that the tank was over flowing so Driver immediately stopped the delivery.  Once the delivery was stopped, Driver went into the building to see how much was in the containment.   Driver noticed approx. 10 gallons in the containment area and nothing was near a drain or got outside the tank containment.  Chemart began to put water on the HCL to start the cleanup process and as a result of this the Acid began to smoke which resulted in the building being evacuated and the fire department being called.   Univar Solutions notified the RIDEM’s spill hotline at 9:07 am to report the release as a precaution as RIDEM’s reportable quantity requires immediate notification for releases where there is a threat or risk of adverse effects on human health (i.e. a need to evacuate a building).    Release was caused by failure of customer's transfer pump which caused an overfill of the smaller day tank.
column169: Customer's pump was replaced.  Univar Solutions is working with customer to see if changes to the delivery set up and procedures could be modified to eliminate the need to transfer from the smaller tank to the larger.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: As a forklift operator was driving by the tote on the dock, the forklift bumped the corner of the tote, causing a crack and material to be released to the dock floor. The released material was immediately neutralized and absorbed using absorbent material. The contents of the release were containerized and labeled for disposal. Packaging specifics could not be safely obtained.
column169: Had the forklift operator verified their clearance before making their turn, this incident would have been prevented. The employee involved in this incident has been counselled per company policy to prevent future incidents.

column168: We were involved in a head on collision where the other driver was traveling in the wrong direction on the interstate. The other driver was cited for DUI. We had significant damage to our tractor and some trailer damage as well. There was approximately 20-50 gallons of fuel that mainly came from  the diesel tank on the tractor. There may have been some minor product loss from the wetlines on the trailer. The trailer integrity was not compromised and there was no product lost from the vessel.   Shield Engineering managed the cleanup and assisted with pumping the product to a different trailer.
column169: Nothing our driver could have done to prevent this crash.

column168: On April 23, 2021, a Customer boarded Flight 1703, A/C N355JB, an Embraer E-190, scheduled to operate from Fort Lauderdale, FL (FLL) to Cartagena, Costa Rica (CTG) with a cell phone attached to a Power Bank (Lithium Polymer).  While settling into his seat, 14C, the Customer dropped the devices.  Upon retrieving them from the floor, there was no apparent damage to the cell phone, but the power bank was getting hot to the touch indicating the possible beginning of Thermal Runaway.  Recognizing what this meant, the Customer notified the Inflight Crewmembers.  The aircraft was five minutes from its scheduled departure time when the Captain was informed of the situation.  All Customers had been boarded by this time.  No clearance to push back or Weight and Balance information had been received as yet.  The Captain reported hearing someone yell "fire" and jumped out of his seat to see what was wrong.  The aircraft was already being evacuated.  The Captain further stated the Power Bank had been moved into the jetbridge where the Inflight Crewmember placed it into a metal trash bin and poured water on it.  It was then carried outside of the jetbridge to the ramp area.  The Captain estimates all Customers were off the aircraft within three minutes of the onset of smoke.  Airport Rescue & Fire Fighting (ARFF) arrived on scene and the Captain asked them to perform a walkthrough of the aircraft where no remaining smoke, fire source, or evidence of fire was found.  JetBlue Technical Operations Crewmembers also did a walkthrough of the cabin to check for damage.  They reported minor damage to the carpeting where the battery was dropped.  The aircraft was removed from service.  The Captain did a check on the Crewmembers and found that one of the Inflight Crewmembers was feeling unwell.  Out of an abundance of caution, the Crewmember was sent for medical review.  After medical review the Crewmember was released.  The Customers were boarded onto another aircraft and the flight departed to its final destination, Cartagena, Costa Rica (CTG).

column168: The incident was reported by the handler ( Emery ) at the airport and noticed when the PMC was offloaded. No product was found outside the PMC ( plastic foil was used ) or in the Aircraft. column169: We had a review with the Handler who did the build up, but nothing was noticed during video check for the build up. After a discussion the most likely is that the skid was build up badly and during transport tore the IBC open resulting in the release of the product. After incident we immediately banned all IBC for UN 3077 until further notice. For future shipments we will ask shipper to add extra material around IBC ( Cardboard, extra plastic ), to use double plastic during build up and supervision of extra person during build up.

column168: On 4/30/21 at 2230 ET, one (1) 55 - gallon metal drum of UN2227, N-Butyl Methacrylate, stabilized, 3, PGIII was discovered to be leaking at the bottom due to a pinhole puncture. As a result, approximately 2 gallons of product released impacting the trailer floor and asphalt below. EnviroServe was dispatched to the site to perform cleanup activities. Upon the contractor's arrival, personnel confirmed a 4' by 9' area of the trailer floor and a small area of asphalt below the trailer had been impacted by approximately 2 gallons of product. EnviroServe personnel overpacked the damaged drum into one (1) 95 gallon overpack drum. The contractor then applied granular absorbents to the impacted trailer floor and asphalt. The spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55 - gallon metal drum. The overpack drum was shipped on to the consignee and the 55 - gallon drum of impacted absorbents was left onsite to be disposed of at a later date.
No cause of damage reported although it seems that spillage occurred during transit.
column169: Make sure all freight is secured before sending through transit.

column168: TRACTOR TRUCK AND CARGO TANK WHERE TRAVERSING STATE HWY 71 NEAR HUGO. CO. THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE TRACTOR AND CARGO TANK WHICH RESULTED IN THE TRACTOR AND CARGO TANK TO ENTER THE HWY 71 WHICH RESULTED IN THE TRACTOR AND CARGO TANK TO ENTER THE HWY 71 DITCH AND THEN ROLLOVER. THE CARGO TANK WAS NOT RUPTURED AND NO PRODUCT WAS LOST. THE CO STATE POLICE AND LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT. THE POLICE REQUESTED AN ENVIRONMENTAL ER CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE. THE GASOLINE AND DIESEL IN THE CARGO TANK WAS TRANSFERRED TO AN EMPTY CARGO TANK. NO PRODUCT WAS LOST DURING THE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT. NO OTHER VEHICLES WHERE INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT. THE DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTED TO A HOSPITAL IN THE DENVER AREA AND ADMITTED. PLEASE SEE THE REQUIRED ATTACHED “INCIDENT REPORT DEATH & INJURY QUESTIONNAIRE.
column169: THE ACCIDENT IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION AND ON-GOING. column168: Driver arrived at customer’s site to make a delivery. The customer said that they were taking full responsibility if anything happens. After a few seconds of unloading, the driver proceeded, and the product started to come out of the top of the tank. Driver stopped the process, but by then, there were approximately three to five gallons of UNL gasoline on the ground.

column168: Load was loaded the morning of April 22 In Leland, NC. Driver proceded toward destination and stopped at Monteagle, Tn for his rest break. At approximately 0430 the driver was awakened by local Fire bept personnel and told to'evacuate vehicle as it was on fire. Investigation proved that the vehide was not on fire, although smoke/vapor was emitting from the trailer. For reasons Still under investigation, a hole(approx 18' x 24"....picture attached) formed in the;trailer. The hole was approximately one third up the height of the trailer, over the rear drive tanden of the tractor. Spillage was contained by sand bag dam. Reminder of load transferred to 10 totes, It is estimated thaf approximately 2000 gallons had leaked from the trailer. Traictor and trailer were washed down. Tractor was able to leave scene with no daniage. A"Shelter In Place" order was issued by local officials that was lifted somewhere between 0900 and 1000.

As our number 3 flight attendant was doing her final walk through the cabin after our safety demo she was stopped by the passenger in seat 26A. The customer had realized she had a small 3.9 oz. canister of propane used for camping in her possession and knew she should not have brought it onboard. The captain was notified and the decision was made to return the aircraft to the gate and remove the propane. The canister was quickly removed and we proceeded with our flight. We would never have known about the canister if the customer had not voluntarily told us. I commend her for her actions in realizing what a potential threat the propane could have been.

column168: Package was offered to the spill office at our Memphis location are the package was reported to have been dropped during sort operations. Part of a, 2 piece multi piece shipment, the package was a UN spec fibreboard box. The box contained 4 glass bottles which were contained in individual plastic moisture barriers. There were fibreboard dividers in the box and packing peanuts used for dunnage. 1 bottle out of the four broke and allowed for an estimated 2.67L to escape. Package was placed in a steel salvage container and shipper was contacted for disposition. An Amended shippers declaration is needed for continued travel.

A Pioneer Transportation cargo tank motor vehicle (CTMV) carrying sodium hydroxide solution was involved in a vehicle accident on US Highway 93 after departing from Pioneer's Henderson, NV facility. The Pioneer Transportation CTMV struck another vehicle that was in the roadway from a previous accident. The Pioneer Transportation CTMV then traveled into the median and rolled onto its side colliding with a concrete abutment. Upon colliding with the concrete abutment, the cargo tank was damaged and experienced a release of an estimated 80 gallons sodium hydroxide solution. There were no injuries as a result of the release. The sodium hydroxide solution remaining in the damaged CTMV was trans-loaded into another CTMV.  All released material was collected in the concrete spillway. Remedial efforts are being conducted by Clean Harbors on Pioneer's behalf, under the supervision of ADOT.  Update to Initial Report: After further review, it was determined that the initial release estimate of 80 galloons did not account for all material released from the CTMV during the event. Based on a material balance (material shipped vs. material returned), the updated release estimate is 139 gallons. Affected area has been remediated by Clean Harbors on Pioneer's behalf.
column169: Implement collision avoidance technology on CTMV to assist with prevention of similar events.

column168: DURING SORT OPERATIONS AT THE FEDEX EXPRESS STATION IN NOVI, MI OPERATIONS STAFF OBSERVED A SHIPMENT IN A METAL DRUM THAT CONTAINED NATURAL ORGANIC LEMON ESSENTIAL OIL. THE SHIPMENT WAS TRAVELING INBOUND FROM CANADA TO THE UNITED STATES. THE DRUM WAS DENTED BUT WAS NOT OBSERVED TO BE LEAKING. ACCORDING TO THE US FDA PRIOR NOTICE FORM SUBMITTED WITH THE SHIPMENT, THE MANUFACTURER OF THE PRODUCT WAS THE LERMOND COMPANY IN NEW JERSEY. THE MANUFACTURER WAS CONTACTED, AND PER THE SAFETY DATA SHEET PROVIDED BY THE MANUFACTURER, THE PARTICULAR ESSENTIAL OIL BEING SHIPPED IS CLASSIFIED AS UN1197 EXTRACTS, FLAVOURING, LIQUID PACKING GROUP III. THERE WERE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE INVOLVED DRUM, AND NO SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WAS OFFERED. THE STATION WAS DIRECTED BY DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION TO HAVE FEDEX SPILL CLEANUP STAFF HOLD THE SHIPMENT PENDING FURTHER DISPOSITION INSTRUCTION.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While beginning to off-load the product at the consignee facility, the tanker began to leak. Off-loading process was terminated. An estimated 3 gallons of product leaked and impacted concrete. The Slay Transportation Co, Inc. driver deployed absorbent material to contain the free liquid. Marion Environmental was dispatched to perform the cleanup and assist with off-loading the tanker.  Marion Environmental arrived and inspected the site. Marion Environmental confirm no soil or storm drains were impacted by the release. Marion Environmental set-up stainless steel pump and proceeded to off-load the product into the consignee's tank. Marion Environmental recovered the spent absorbent material and placed into a drum for disposal.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence. However, Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Part of a multi piece shipment, box 1 of 3 boxes (Master TRK# 931192650373) was leaking and all contents were placed in a steel salvage package at our Memphis hub location. It is unknown and not reported how the damage occurred tot he package. Shipper contacted for an amended shippers declaration for continued travel.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: At 15:30 on 4/19/2021, a Kansas City Southern Railway(KCS) train crew working in the KCS Westlake, LA rail yard discovered loaded Hazmat tank car TCIX 259012 Ieaklng from the top of the car. The KCS Environmental& Hazmat Dept. mobillzed railroad qualified response contractors to investigate, monitor, and mltigate the leak. Upon arrival, TCIX 259012 was found Ieaklng from the reclosing pressure relief device. The car was found to be overfilled, which resulted In the release. Responders decontaminated the exterior of the car. The car was reduced by transloading product Into a vacuum truck, which was then moved to destination. The car was properly secured, verified not Ieaking, and then released back into transportation. A KCS crew member sought medical attention after coming into proximity of TCIX 259012. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package Is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway(KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases(NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal Injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adJacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases(a.k.a. package closure Issues such as this), the shipper Is requested to conduct a rootcause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.(Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs. (NAR: 419)

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. Upon unloading, a leak was discovered inside the trailer. Site was secured and SDS was consulted. Clean Harbors Environmental Services was dispatched to assess and perform the cleanup. Upon inspection, one 5-gallon pail was discovered crushed by heavy freight as a result of improper loading and bracing. Approximately 5 gallons of free product released to the trailer floor and concrete surface beneath trailer. Clean Harbors Environmental Services applied absorbent material to the free liquid and secured the area. Clean Harbors Environmental Services returned the following day, offloaded the trailer, applied additional absorbent material to the free product, and swept all spent absorbent material into recovery drums. Contaminated pallet was broken down and containerized along wtih damaged drum. Trailer was cleaned, remaining freight was repalletized, and reloaded, and 3 55-gallon drums of spent absorbents material, contaminated pallet wood, PPE and cleanup debris were generated. Disposal was coordinated in accordance with local state and federal regulations.
column169: N&M Transfer will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: A Pioneer Transportation cargo tank motor vehicle (CTMV) carrying sodium hydroxide solution was involved in a vehicle accident on US Highway 93 after departing from Pioneer's Henderson, NV facility. The Pioneer Transportation CTMV struck another vehicle that was in the roadway from a previous accident. The Pioneer Transportation CTMV then traveled into the median and rolled onto its side colliding with a concrete abutment. Upon colliding with the concrete abutment, the cargo tank was damaged and experienced a release of an estimated 80 gallons of sodium hydroxide solution. There were no injuries as a result of the release. The sodium hydroxide solution remaining in the damaged CTMV was trans-loaded into another CTMV.  All released material was collected in the concrete spillway. Remedial efforts are being conducted by Clean Harbors on Pioneer's behalf, under the supervision of ADOT.

column168: The load had three stops. After the first stop, the driver put a strap across the back of two hazmat totes before departing for the next stop. He noticed one of the totes was at a slight angle but added the strap thinking it would be ok. Because the tote was at a slight angle it allowed the strap to make contact with the corner of the plastic IBC instead of the metal cage. During his drive the strap was making contact with the plastic on the corner causing extra pressure on the point. As a result a crack developed in the plastic allowing a slow leak. As soon as it was discovered the driver called in and was instructed to stay in place and wait for a clean up crew to arrive and do cleanup. The driver was at the flying J in Lebanon IN where he waited for cleanup. The strap caused a crack approximately four inches wide. It was on the tote corner approximately14 inches from the top of the tote. It leaked a potential maximum of about 1.5 hours. Upon discovery the drive parked and waited for cleanup. Emergency Management Inc out of Oklahoma sent a local contractor out to clean up the product and make the trailer safe for transport.
column169: Due to the incident we reviewed our whole cargo securement process for improvements from the loading dock to the drivers transporting. With most all of our cargo we are able to use straps on the packaging with no issues to securement or damage to product containers. The flammable tote cages were an area we could make improvement to keep the strap from contacting the plastic totes. We are going to incorporate Veeboards to cover the corner of the totes so the strap will not be able to make contact. The toes will be loaded next to the side and the strap wrapped around the tote to secure it to the side and another strap behind and in front as needed.  Loading personnel are retrained on cargo securement with the new process and a renewed awareness of potential issues and the consequences. The drivers were additionally informed of the new process and encouraged to provide feedback on cargo securement through our feedback process.
